AI-Based Exam Anxiety Detector
Project Documentation
1. Introduction

Examinations are a significant source of stress and anxiety for students. Academic pressure, fear of failure, and performance expectations often lead to emotional distress that can negatively impact both mental health and academic performance. Many students experience anxiety but may not always have access to immediate support or guidance.

The AI-Based Exam Anxiety Detector is designed to address this issue by analyzing exam-related text inputs and predicting the level of anxiety expressed by a student. Using Natural Language Processing (NLP) techniques and a BERT-based deep learning model, the system can interpret emotional cues in user-written text and classify them into different anxiety levels.

The goal of this project is to create an intelligent and user-friendly platform that allows students to express their feelings and receive supportive feedback and simple anxiety-management suggestions.

2. Objectives

The primary objectives of the project are:

To develop an AI model capable of detecting exam-related anxiety from textual input.

To create a backend API that processes text and returns anxiety predictions.

To design a user-friendly frontend interface for students to interact with the system.

To provide supportive suggestions that help users manage exam-related stress.

To demonstrate the practical application of NLP and deep learning in mental health awareness.

3. System Architecture

The system follows a client-server architecture, consisting of three main components:

Frontend Interface

The frontend is built using Streamlit, which provides a simple and interactive web interface for users to enter exam-related text and view predictions.

Backend API

The backend is implemented using FastAPI, which handles incoming requests from the frontend, processes the text using the trained model, and returns predictions.

AI Model

A BERT-based classification model is used to analyze the emotional context of the input text and determine the corresponding anxiety level.

Architecture Flow

User Input → Frontend (Streamlit) → FastAPI Backend → BERT Model → Prediction → Frontend Display

