5. Dataset Description

The dataset used for training contains text samples representing different levels of exam-related anxiety. These samples include student statements expressing stress, nervousness, confidence, or emotional distress regarding exams.

The dataset was preprocessed before training to ensure quality and consistency. Preprocessing steps included:

Removing unnecessary characters and formatting

Converting text into lowercase

Tokenizing sentences using the BERT tokenizer

Encoding text into numerical representations suitable for model training

The dataset was divided into training and validation sets to ensure proper model evaluation.

6. Model Development

The core of the system is a BERT-based text classification model.

BERT is a powerful transformer-based NLP model capable of understanding contextual meaning in sentences. It is particularly effective for tasks such as sentiment analysis and emotion detection.

Model Workflow

Input text is tokenized using the BERT tokenizer.

The tokenized text is converted into embeddings.

The BERT model processes the embeddings to understand context.

A classification layer predicts the anxiety category.

The model classifies input text into categories such as:

Low Anxiety

Moderate Anxiety

High Anxiety

The trained model is saved and later loaded by the backend server for real-time inference.

7. Backend Implementation

The backend is built using FastAPI, which exposes a REST API for making predictions.

Key backend components include:

Loading the trained BERT model

Defining request and response schemas

Implementing the prediction endpoint

Running the API server

The main API endpoint is:

POST /predict

It receives user text and returns the predicted anxiety level in JSON format.

Example request:

{
"text": "I feel nervous before my exams"
}

Example response:

{
"anxiety_level": "Moderate Anxiety"
}

The backend server is launched using Uvicorn.

8. Frontend Implementation

The frontend is implemented using Streamlit, allowing users to interact with the system through a web interface.

Key features of the frontend include:

Text input area for exam-related thoughts

Button to submit input for analysis

Instant display of predicted anxiety level

Emoji-based feedback for visual clarity

Simple anxiety-management tips

Visualization charts showing prediction confidence

The frontend communicates with the backend using HTTP requests and displays the prediction results in a clear and user-friendly manner.

9. Results and Output

When a user enters text describing their feelings about exams, the system analyzes the input and predicts the corresponding anxiety level.

Example outputs:

Input:
"I feel extremely nervous about tomorrow's exam."

Output:
High Anxiety

Input:
"I studied well but still feel slightly worried."

Output:
Moderate Anxiety

The system then provides helpful suggestions to support the user.

10. Applications

The AI-Based Exam Anxiety Detector can be applied in several areas:

Student mental health awareness platforms

Educational institutions

Academic counseling support tools

Online learning environments

Early stress detection systems

11. Limitations

While the system demonstrates the application of AI in anxiety detection, certain limitations exist:

The model relies solely on textual input.

Anxiety levels are estimated and not clinically validated.

The system cannot replace professional psychological assessment.

Accuracy depends on dataset quality and diversity.

12. Future Improvements

Future enhancements may include:

Expanding the dataset for better model accuracy

Detecting more detailed emotional states

Adding voice-based emotion detection

Tracking anxiety trends over time

Integrating AI-based conversational support

Deploying the application as a cloud-based service

13. Conclusion

The AI-Based Exam Anxiety Detector demonstrates how machine learning and natural language processing can be used to analyze emotional expressions in text and provide supportive feedback to students.

By combining a BERT-based NLP model, FastAPI backend, and Streamlit frontend, the project creates a complete AI-powered system capable of real-time anxiety detection. The project highlights the potential of AI technologies in addressing mental health awareness and providing accessible digital support tools for students.